\Abstract

Using the monster/Semple tower construction, we study the structure of the Cartan prolongation of the family x1​x2=tsubscript𝑥1subscript𝑥2𝑡x_{1}x_{2}=t of plane curves with nodal central member.

\Keywords

curve families; nodal singularity; vector distributions; prolongation \Classification58A30; 53A55; 58K50; 14D06; 14H99

1 Introduction

The familiar process of implicit differentiation, when applied k𝑘k times to the equation f​(x,y)=0𝑓𝑥𝑦0f(x,y)=0 of a nonsingular plane curve C𝐶C, yields a system of equations

f=0,𝑓0\displaystyle f=0,
fx+fy​y′=0,subscript𝑓𝑥subscript𝑓𝑦superscript𝑦′0\displaystyle f_{x}+f_{y}y^{\prime}=0,
fx​x+(2​fy​x+fy​y​y′)​y′+fy​y′′=0,subscript𝑓𝑥𝑥2subscript𝑓𝑦𝑥subscript𝑓𝑦𝑦superscript𝑦′superscript𝑦′subscript𝑓𝑦superscript𝑦′′0\displaystyle f_{xx}+(2f_{yx}+f_{yy}y^{\prime})y^{\prime}+f_{y}y^{\prime\prime}=0,
⋮⋮\displaystyle\quad\vdots
fx​⋯​x+⋯+fy​y(k)=0.subscript𝑓𝑥⋯𝑥⋯subscript𝑓𝑦superscript𝑦𝑘0\displaystyle f_{x\cdots x}+\cdots+f_{y}y^{(k)}=0. (1.1)

One can interpret (1.1) as a system defining a curve in a (k+2)𝑘2(k+2)-dimensional manifold. Indeed, at each point of C𝐶C where fy≠0subscript𝑓𝑦0f_{y}\neq 0, the equations of (1.1) determine unique values of y′,y′′,…,y(k)superscript𝑦′superscript𝑦′′…superscript𝑦𝑘y^{\prime},y^{\prime\prime},\ldots,y^{(k)}, which we will call the curvilinear data. At points where fy=0subscript𝑓𝑦0f_{y}=0 (i.e., at which the tangent line is vertical), one can reverse the roles of the variables, and the resulting system will determine values of x′=d​x/d​y,x′′,…,x(k)superscript𝑥′𝑑𝑥𝑑𝑦superscript𝑥′′…superscript𝑥𝑘x^{\prime}={d}x/{d}y,x^{\prime\prime},\ldots,x^{(k)}. In the literature of differential geometry, this process of obtaining a curve in a higher-dimensional space is often called prolongation.

The notion of prolongation dates back to Cartan’s 1914 paper [4]. It was introduced as a means of understanding when two systems of differential equations should be considered to be equivalent. As explained by Bryant (in Section 6.2 of the unpublished lecture notes [2]), “Intuitively, prolongation is just differentiating the equations you have and then adjoining those equations as new equations in the system”. Further discussion of the idea can be found in [3, Section 4.2].

One can also prolong a singular curve. To make sense of this assertion, one needs to understand how to deal with the possibility that the higher-order curvilinear data may “become infinite”. In other words, one needs to explain how to compactify the manifold of nonsingular curvilinear data. There is an elegant compactification, first explained in the literature of differential geometry by Montgomery and Zhitomirskii [16, 17]. Starting with an arbitrary surface S𝑆S, their monster tower is a sequence

⋯→S​(k)→S​(k−1)→⋯→S​(2)→S​(1)→S​(0)=S→⋯𝑆𝑘→𝑆𝑘1→⋯→𝑆2→𝑆1→𝑆0𝑆\displaystyle\cdots\to S(k)\to S(k-1)\to\cdots\to S(2)\to S(1)\to S(0)=S

in which each S​(k)→S​(k−1)→𝑆𝑘𝑆𝑘1S(k)\to S(k-1) is a fiber bundle with fiber ℙ1superscriptℙ1\mathbb{P}^{1}. The equations of (1.1) can now be interpreted as a calculation within one of two regular charts of S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k). A similar calculation can be carried out for any curve in S𝑆S, and for a singular curve it will lead to curves that leave the regular charts. Their work on the monster construction was motivated in part by a body of literature about Goursat distributions, including classification of their possible singularities and the appearance of moduli in this classification; as representative contributions we mention [10] and [18].

At about the time of the publication of the Montgomery–Zhitomirskii monograph [17], it was observed by Alex Castro that in fact the monster construction was already known in algebraic geometry, in literature beginning with Gherardelli [9] and Semple [19]. In this strand of literature, instead of “prolongation” one will find “Nash blowup” and “lifting”; here the tower is called the Semple bundle tower. Our own contributions were in the papers [6, 7, 8].

In [15], Cartan prolongation is applied to resolution of plane curves. This study naturally leads to the following problem, stated as Problem A in the last section of the cited paper: “Investigate the extent to which deformation and prolongation of curves commute”. In this note we offer a response, based on the standard theory of extension of a flat family over a punctured one-dimensional base, as in Proposition 9.8 of Hartshorne’s text [11].

For the moment, we have just written an account of the theory in the simplest nontrivial case: a family 𝒳𝒳{\mathcal{X}} of curves x1​x2=tsubscript𝑥1subscript𝑥2𝑡x_{1}x_{2}=t. Here x1subscript𝑥1x_{1} and x2subscript𝑥2x_{2} are local coordinates on a neighborhood U𝑈U of a point on a surface S𝑆S, and t𝑡t is a local coordinate on a neighborhood T𝑇T of 00 on the line. (We use subscripted notations to be consistent with the coordinates introduced in Section 3.) The central member of the family is the nodal curve x1​x2=0subscript𝑥1subscript𝑥20x_{1}x_{2}=0. We are asking what happens when one tries to prolong all members of the family. For t≠0𝑡0t\neq 0 the process of prolongation, carried out k𝑘k times, gives us a family of nonsingular curves on the monster space S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k). What happens over t=0𝑡0t=0?

Hartshorne’s Proposition 9.8 says that there is a unique extension to a flat family defined even over t=0𝑡0t=0. The total space of the family of k𝑘kth order prolongations (including the central member) will be denoted by 𝒳​(k)𝒳𝑘{\mathcal{X}}(k); it is a subvariety of S​(k)×T𝑆𝑘𝑇S(k)\times T. The members of the family will be denoted by X​(k)t𝑋subscript𝑘𝑡X(k)_{t}; we call the central member X​(k)0𝑋subscript𝑘0X(k)_{0} the prolongation of the nodal curve. Here we will work out an explicit description of the central member: it consists of 2k+1superscript2𝑘12^{k}+1 irreducible components, which we call twigs. The twigs meet at ordinary nodes, forming a chain; only the two curves at the ends will be reduced schemes. When reduced, each twig (except the two at the ends) is a copy of the projective line. The two end twigs are the Cartan prolongations of x2=0subscript𝑥20x_{2}=0 (which we call the left end) and of x1=0subscript𝑥10x_{1}=0 (the right end). The other twigs will be called interior twigs. Fig. 1 shows the case k=3𝑘3k=3.

Again by standard theory, the flat family 𝒳​(k)𝒳𝑘{\mathcal{X}}(k) of curves gives a family of 1-dimensional cycle classes. For t≠0𝑡0t\neq 0 this class is just the fundamental class of the k𝑘kth prolongation of Xtsubscript𝑋𝑡X_{t}. The class associated to the central member will be denoted by Z​(k)0𝑍subscript𝑘0Z(k)_{0}. As we will see, it is a linear combination of fundamental classes of the 2k+1superscript2𝑘12^{k}+1 curves mentioned above, and (except for the two curves at the end) the coefficients will be greater than 1.

We begin in Section 2 by briefly recalling the construction of the monster tower and explaining prolongation of a curve into it. In Section 3 we describe a natural system of charts on the spaces in the monster tower, citing the general description of [5] but specializing to the case of a 2-dimensional base. In Section 4 we give equations defining 𝒳​(k)𝒳𝑘{\mathcal{X}}(k) in each of these charts; from these equations we immediately deduce the irreducible components, i.e., the twigs. Section 5 describes the multiplicities of these twigs. Again referring to our earlier work (joint with Castro and Shanbrom) in [5], in Section 6 we analyze how the twigs meet the strata of the natural coarse stratification of the monster space. We illustrate the ideas by a running example, beginning with Example 3.1. Finally in Section 7, we briefly speculate about what one should expect if one carries out a similar analysis for a locally irreducible curve singularity such as y2=xnsuperscript𝑦2superscript𝑥𝑛y^{2}=x^{n}.

2 The monster tower; prolongation of curves

We begin by briefly explaining the construction of the monster tower, closely following the account in Section 1 of our recent paper with Castro and Shanbrom [5]. That paper also gives a brief history of the construction, which was discovered independently in two separate strands of the mathematical literature. (For other treatments, see [16, 17], or our ancient papers [6, 7, 8].)

Suppose that M𝑀M is a smooth manifold or nonsingular algebraic variety over an algebraically closed field 𝐤𝐤{\mathbf{k}} of characteristic 0. Suppose that ℬℬ{\mathcal{B}} is a rank b𝑏b subbundle of its tangent bundle T​M𝑇𝑀TM. Let M~=ℙ​ℬ~𝑀ℙℬ\widetilde{M}=\mathbb{P}{\mathcal{B}}, the total space of the projectivization of the bundle, and let π:M~→M:𝜋→~𝑀𝑀\pi\colon\widetilde{M}\to M be the projection. A point p~~𝑝\widetilde{p} of M~=ℙ​ℬ~𝑀ℙℬ\widetilde{M}=\mathbb{P}{\mathcal{B}} over p∈M𝑝𝑀p\in M represents a line inside the fiber of ℬℬ{\mathcal{B}} at p𝑝p, and since ℬℬ{\mathcal{B}} is a subbundle of T​M𝑇𝑀TM, this is a tangent direction to M𝑀M at p𝑝p. Let

d​π:T​M~→π∗​T​M:𝑑𝜋→𝑇~𝑀superscript𝜋𝑇𝑀\displaystyle{d}\pi\colon\ T{\widetilde{M}}\to\pi^{*}TM

denote the derivative map of π𝜋\pi. A tangent vector to M~~𝑀\widetilde{M} at p~~𝑝\widetilde{p} is said to be a focal vector if it is mapped by d​π𝑑𝜋{d}\pi to a tangent vector at p𝑝p in the direction represented by p~~𝑝\widetilde{p}; in particular a vector mapping to the zero vector (called a vertical vector) is considered to be a focal vector. The set of all focal vectors forms a subbundle ℬ~~ℬ\widetilde{\mathcal{B}} of T​M~𝑇~𝑀T{\widetilde{M}}, called the focal bundle; its rank is again b𝑏b. Thus we can iterate this construction to obtain a tower of spaces (i.e., smooth manifolds or nonsingular algebraic varieties) together with their associated bundles.

If we begin this construction with a surface S𝑆S, taking ℬℬ{\mathcal{B}} to be its tangent bundle, then the resulting tower

⋯→S​(k)→πkS​(k−1)→πk−1⋯→S​(2)→S​(1)→S​(0)=S→⋯𝑆𝑘subscript𝜋𝑘→𝑆𝑘1subscript𝜋𝑘1→⋯→𝑆2→𝑆1→𝑆0𝑆\displaystyle\cdots\to S(k)\xrightarrow{\pi_{k}}S(k-1)\xrightarrow{\pi_{k-1}}\cdots\to S(2)\to S(1)\to S(0)=S

is called the monster tower, and the spaces S​(1),S​(2),…𝑆1𝑆2…S(1),S(2),\ldots are called monster spaces. Observe that each S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k) is the total space of a ℙ1superscriptℙ1\mathbb{P}^{1}-bundle over S​(k−1)𝑆𝑘1S(k-1); in particular, S​(1)𝑆1S(1) is the total space of the tangent bundle ℙ​T​Sℙ𝑇𝑆\mathbb{P}TS. Sometimes we say that S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k) is the monster space at level k𝑘k. If p𝑝p is a point of S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k), we will say that it lies over πk​(p)subscript𝜋𝑘𝑝\pi_{k}(p) and over πk−1​πk​(p)subscript𝜋𝑘1subscript𝜋𝑘𝑝\pi_{k-1}\pi_{k}(p), etc. The associated rank 2 focal bundle on S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k) will be denoted by ℬ​(k)ℬ𝑘{\mathcal{B}}(k).

Now consider a nonsingular point p𝑝p of a curve C𝐶C in S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k). We can associate to p𝑝p the point of ℙ​T​S​(k)ℙ𝑇𝑆𝑘\mathbb{P}TS(k) representing the tangent direction of C𝐶C at p𝑝p. Thus, away from singularities, we have a curve C~~𝐶\widetilde{C} in ℙ​T​S​(k)ℙ𝑇𝑆𝑘\mathbb{P}T{S(k)}, the prolongation or lift. Now suppose that C𝐶C itself is the prolongation of a curve from S​(k−1)𝑆𝑘1S(k-1). Note that this curve is πk​(C)subscript𝜋𝑘𝐶\pi_{k}(C); thus the tangent vectors to C~~𝐶\widetilde{C} are focal vectors. Therefore C~~𝐶\widetilde{C} is in fact a curve in S​(k+1)𝑆𝑘1S(k+1).

We also want to lift a singular curve C𝐶C in S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k), and we do so by fiat: we lift at all nonsingular points of C𝐶C, and then take the closure. If, away from the singularity, C𝐶C is obtained from lifting a curve in S​(k−1)𝑆𝑘1S(k-1), then again C~~𝐶\widetilde{C} lies entirely within S​(k+1)𝑆𝑘1S(k+1). For example, the lift of the plane curve x​y=0𝑥𝑦0xy=0 will consist of two irreducible curves, the lifts of its individual nonsingular components x=0𝑥0x=0 and y=0𝑦0y=0. Note that this is not what we have previously called the prolongation of the nodal curve, since here we are considering the curve by itself, without reference to the family in which it is situated. Similarly, the lift of the cuspidal curve y2=x3superscript𝑦2superscript𝑥3y^{2}=x^{3} will be a nonsingular curve; note that it is tangent to the fiber of S​(1)𝑆1S(1) over the origin.

Consider the ℙ1superscriptℙ1\mathbb{P}^{1}-fiber of S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k) over a point of S​(k−1)𝑆𝑘1S(k-1); following [17, Definition 2.17], we call it a vertical curve. Note that its prolongation is a curve in S​(k+1)𝑆𝑘1S(k+1); indeed, all of the tangent vectors are vertical. This curve will be called the prolongation of a vertical curve, and we apply the same terminology to the curves obtained by further prolongation.

In the literature of differential geometry, e.g., [18], the monster tower emerges from a study of Goursat distributions. The fundamental work [16] shows that locally each Goursat distribution arises from the prolongation of a suitable curve on a surface. This construction is not canonical; that is, two different curves may lead to the same Goursat distribution. Perhaps the simplest example begins with the singular parametrized curve x=t2𝑥superscript𝑡2x=t^{2}, y=t3𝑦superscript𝑡3y=t^{3}, whose prolongation yields the curve

x=t2,y=t3,y′=32​t,formulae-sequence𝑥superscript𝑡2formulae-sequence𝑦superscript𝑡3superscript𝑦′32𝑡\displaystyle x=t^{2},\qquad y=t^{3},\qquad y^{\prime}=\frac{3}{2}t,

where y′=d​y/d​xsuperscript𝑦′𝑑𝑦𝑑𝑥y^{\prime}={d}y/{d}x. This is a curve on a chart of S​(1)𝑆1S(1). On may also begin with the nonsingular curve x¯=32​t¯𝑥32𝑡\overline{x}=\frac{3}{2}t, y¯=t3¯𝑦superscript𝑡3\overline{y}=t^{3}, and prolong it to

x¯=32​t,y¯=t3,y¯′=2​t2,formulae-sequence¯𝑥32𝑡formulae-sequence¯𝑦superscript𝑡3superscript¯𝑦′2superscript𝑡2\displaystyle\overline{x}=\frac{3}{2}t,\qquad\overline{y}=t^{3},\qquad\overline{y}^{\prime}=2t^{2},

where y¯′=d​y¯/d​x¯superscript¯𝑦′𝑑¯𝑦𝑑¯𝑥\overline{y}^{\prime}={d}\overline{y}/{d}\overline{x}. The declarations x¯=y′¯𝑥superscript𝑦′\overline{x}=y^{\prime}, y¯=y¯𝑦𝑦\overline{y}=y, y¯′=2​xsuperscript¯𝑦′2𝑥\overline{y}^{\prime}=2x identify the two prolongations. Thus in the differential-geometric literature one sees no distinction between the resulting Goursat distributions. For us, however, the fundamental object is the curve on the base rather than the distribution at level 111.

We were aware of this ambiguity when we wrote [7], in which we observed (on page 35) that the Semple bundle tower over the projective plane ℙ2superscriptℙ2\mathbb{P}^{2} is the same as the Semple bundle tower over the dual projective plane ℙˇ2superscriptˇℙ2\check{\mathbb{P}}^{2}. This means that if one considers, as in classical projective geometry, a curve C⊂ℙ2𝐶superscriptℙ2C\subset\mathbb{P}^{2} and its dual curve Cˇ⊂ℙˇ2ˇ𝐶superscriptˇℙ2\check{C}\subset\check{\mathbb{P}}^{2}, they have the same prolongation, considered as a curve in the incidence correspondence of points and lines, which can be identified with ℙ2​(1)superscriptℙ21\mathbb{P}^{2}(1). This is the key fact in understanding the classical Plücker formulas (see [1, Section 9.1]).

3 Coordinate charts on the monster tower

We now recall a natural system of 2ksuperscript2𝑘2^{k} coordinate charts on the k𝑘kth monster space. They are essentially the coordinates first described in [10] and [13] in a study of Pfaffian systems; in the subsequent literature of differential geometry, they are known as Kumpera–Ruiz coordinates. Independently and in a seemingly different context, we developed coordinate systems for the Semple bundle tower over a base surface [6, 7, 8]. The paper [16] shows that the Kumpera–Ruiz coordinates are coordinates on the monster spaces; Castro’s later realization that the Semple bundle and monster tower constructions are the same thus implies that the two notions of coordinate systems must agree. These coordinates were extended to towers over higher-dimensional base manifolds and systematized in [14]. In [5], we explained a convenient general method for naming these coordinates. We use that method here, specializing to the case where the base is a surface.

Each chart is a copy of U×𝔸k𝑈superscript𝔸𝑘U\times\mathbb{A}^{k}, the product of the base neighborhood U𝑈U and k𝑘k-dimensional affine space, and on each chart there are k+2𝑘2k+2 coordinate functions: the pullback of x1subscript𝑥1x_{1} and x2subscript𝑥2x_{2} from U𝑈U, together with k𝑘k affine coordinates. By a recursive procedure, two of these coordinates will be designated as active coordinates. One will be identified as the new coordinate and denoted by 𝐧𝐧{\mathbf{n}}, and the other will be identified as the retained coordinate and denoted by 𝐫𝐫{\mathbf{r}}. In addition (for k>0𝑘0k>0) a third coordinate will be designated as the deactivated coordinate and denoted by 𝐝𝐝{\mathbf{d}}. At each point p𝑝p of the chart, the fiber of ℬ​(k)ℬ𝑘{\mathcal{B}}(k) consists of tangent vectors for which either d​𝐧𝑑𝐧d{\mathbf{n}} or d​𝐫𝑑𝐫d{\mathbf{r}} is nonzero. Here is the recursive procedure: beginning with a chart with 𝐧𝐧{\mathbf{n}}, 𝐫𝐫{\mathbf{r}}, and 𝐝𝐝{\mathbf{d}} (plus k−1𝑘1k-1 unnamed coordinates), create two charts at the next level by choosing one of the following two options:

  • •

    Assuming the differential d​𝐫𝑑𝐫d{\mathbf{r}} is nonzero, let 𝐍=d​𝐧/d​𝐫𝐍𝑑𝐧𝑑𝐫{\mathbf{N}}=d{\mathbf{n}}/d{\mathbf{r}}; then set 𝐑=𝐫𝐑𝐫{\mathbf{R}}={\mathbf{r}} and 𝐃=𝐧𝐃𝐧{\mathbf{D}}={\mathbf{n}}. (We call this the regular choice.)

  • •

    Assuming the differential d​𝐧𝑑𝐧d{\mathbf{n}} is nonzero, let 𝐍=d​𝐫/d​𝐧𝐍𝑑𝐫𝑑𝐧{\mathbf{N}}=d{\mathbf{r}}/d{\mathbf{n}}; then set 𝐑=𝐧𝐑𝐧{\mathbf{R}}={\mathbf{n}} and 𝐃=𝐫𝐃𝐫{\mathbf{D}}={\mathbf{r}}. (We call this the critical choice.)

We remark that in either case we have

𝐍=d​𝐃d​𝐑.𝐍𝑑𝐃𝑑𝐑\displaystyle{\mathbf{N}}=\frac{{d}{\mathbf{D}}}{{d}{\mathbf{R}}}. (3.1)

To begin the process we always make a regular choice, but there are two possibilities. On U𝑈U the active coordinates are x1subscript𝑥1x_{1} and x2subscript𝑥2x_{2}, either of which may be designated as the retained coordinate, and there is no deactivated coordinate.

Our labeling of charts will use the alphabet {1,2}12\{1,2\}. We will find it convenient to use the following notational device: p¯¯𝑝\overline{p} denotes the symbol opposite to p𝑝p, i.e., 1¯=2¯12\overline{1}=2 and 2¯=1¯21\overline{2}=1.

Each chart on S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k) will be labeled by 𝒞​(p1​p2​⋯​pk)𝒞subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘{\mathcal{C}}(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k}), where p1​p2​⋯​pksubscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k} is a string from the alphabet. In particular 𝒞​(∅)𝒞{\mathcal{C}}(\varnothing) is U𝑈U itself. In 𝒞​(p1​p2​⋯​pk)𝒞subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘{\mathcal{C}}(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k}), we will use 2​(k+1)2𝑘12(k+1) coordinate names

x1,x1​(p1),x1​(p1​p2),x1​(p1​p2​p3),…,x1​(p1​p2​⋯​pk),subscript𝑥1subscript𝑥1subscript𝑝1subscript𝑥1subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2subscript𝑥1subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2subscript𝑝3…subscript𝑥1subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘\displaystyle x_{1},\enskip x_{1}(p_{1}),\enskip x_{1}(p_{1}p_{2}),\enskip x_{1}(p_{1}p_{2}p_{3}),\enskip\ldots,\enskip x_{1}(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k}),

Note that the image of an interior twig under πksubscript𝜋𝑘\pi_{k} is determined by the images of its two nodes: if the nodes map to the same node, then the entire twig is mapped to this node as well; otherwise it maps to the twig determined by the two image nodes. Concretely, the label of a twig is obtained from the labels of its nodes by using the longest possible common initial string. Refer to Fig. 1 to see how this works at level 3.

6 Stratification

Together with Castro and Shanbrom, we have worked out in [5] the details of a natural coarse stratification of the monster spaces. We briefly recall that theory here, specializing to the case where the base is a surface. The basic idea is to apply the construction of Section 2 in a different way. Assuming that k≥2𝑘2k\geq 2, we begin with M=S​(k−1)𝑀𝑆𝑘1M=S(k-1) and ℬℬ{\mathcal{B}} the bundle of vertical vectors at level k−1𝑘1k-1. This is a rank 1 bundle, and thus M~~𝑀\widetilde{M} is a copy of S​(k−1)𝑆𝑘1S(k-1) inside S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k); moreover it is a divisor meeting each ℙ1superscriptℙ1\mathbb{P}^{1}-fiber in one point. We call M~~𝑀\widetilde{M} the divisor at infinity and denote it by Iksubscript𝐼𝑘I_{k}. Iterating the process, we obtain subspaces Ik​[1]subscript𝐼𝑘delimited-[]1I_{k}[1] in S​(k+1)𝑆𝑘1S(k+1), then Ik​[2]subscript𝐼𝑘delimited-[]2I_{k}[2] in S​(k+2)𝑆𝑘2S(k+2), etc. (By convention Ik​[0]=Iksubscript𝐼𝑘delimited-[]0subscript𝐼𝑘I_{k}[0]=I_{k}.) Each Ik​[n]subscript𝐼𝑘delimited-[]𝑛I_{k}[n] is a copy of S​(k−1)𝑆𝑘1S(k-1), having codimension n+1𝑛1n+1 inside S​(k+n)𝑆𝑘𝑛S(k+n). We remark that if we prolong the fiber of S​(k−1)𝑆𝑘1S(k-1) over a point of S​(k−2)𝑆𝑘2S(k-2), i.e., a vertical curve then its successive prolongations lie on these Ik​[n]subscript𝐼𝑘delimited-[]𝑛I_{k}[n]’s.

In [5], we examined the intersection locus

IW=⋂j=2kIj​[nj−1],subscript𝐼𝑊superscriptsubscript𝑗2𝑘subscript𝐼𝑗delimited-[]subscript𝑛𝑗1\displaystyle I_{W}=\bigcap_{j=2}^{k}I_{j}[n_{j}-1], (6.1)

a subspace of S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k). We will explain the notation on the left side of (6.1) in a moment. To make sense of the notations on the right side, we need to make several remarks. First, each njsubscript𝑛𝑗n_{j} is a nonnegative integer with nj≤k−j+1subscript𝑛𝑗𝑘𝑗1n_{j}\leq k-j+1. The space Ij​[nj−1]subscript𝐼𝑗delimited-[]subscript𝑛𝑗1I_{j}[n_{j}-1] has been defined to be a subspace of S​(nj+j−1)𝑆subscript𝑛𝑗𝑗1S(n_{j}+j-1); in (6.1) we use its complete inverse image in S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k). We have already remarked that Ij​[0]subscript𝐼𝑗delimited-[]0I_{j}[0] means Ijsubscript𝐼𝑗I_{j}, and we interpret Ij​[−1]subscript𝐼𝑗delimited-[]1I_{j}[-1] as S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k) itself (so that this intersectand could be omitted). With these conventions, the intersection locus of (6.1), if it is not empty, is nonsingular and of codimension n2+n3+⋯+nksubscript𝑛2subscript𝑛3⋯subscript𝑛𝑘n_{2}+n_{3}+\cdots+n_{k}.

To understand when these loci are nonempty, we work with certain code words

W=VA1​VA2​VA3​⋯​VAk𝑊subscript𝑉subscript𝐴1subscript𝑉subscript𝐴2subscript𝑉subscript𝐴3⋯subscript𝑉subscript𝐴𝑘\displaystyle W=V_{A_{1}}V_{A_{2}}V_{A_{3}}\cdots V_{A_{k}} (6.2)

created according to the following rules:

  1. 1)

    the first subscript A1subscript𝐴1A_{1} must be ∅\varnothing;

  2. 2)

    for j≥2𝑗2j\geq 2, the subscript Ajsubscript𝐴𝑗A_{j} must be ∅\varnothing or j𝑗j or the prior subscript Aj−1subscript𝐴𝑗1A_{j-1}.

The symbol V∅subscript𝑉V_{\varnothing} is also denoted R𝑅R; in particular the first symbol is always R𝑅R. The number of code words of length k𝑘k is the Fibonacci number F2​k−1subscript𝐹2𝑘1F_{2k-1} (where F1=F2=1subscript𝐹1subscript𝐹21F_{1}=F_{2}=1). Let njsubscript𝑛𝑗n_{j} denote the total number of times that j𝑗j appears in the subscripts of W𝑊W; then the intersection locus IWsubscript𝐼𝑊I_{W} specified by (6.1) is nonempty, and this method accounts for all nonempty intersection loci.

Example 6.1.

There are five code words of length three, and thus five associated intersection loci on S​(3)𝑆3S(3):

The intersection loci of (6.1) are nested in a straightforward way: given code words W′superscript𝑊′W^{\prime} and W𝑊W whose respective associated integers satisfy nj′≥njsubscriptsuperscript𝑛′𝑗subscript𝑛𝑗n^{\prime}_{j}\geq n_{j} (for each j=2,…,k𝑗2…𝑘j=2,\ldots,k), the intersection locus IW′subscript𝐼superscript𝑊′I_{W^{\prime}} is contained in IWsubscript𝐼𝑊I_{W}. Removing all the lower-dimensional loci from an intersection locus gives a code word stratum, an open dense subset of the intersection locus. In this manner we have stratified S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k), as in [5]. In that paper we also gave equations defining each intersection locus in each chart; all of them are linear equations in the local coordinates. Each stratum is obtained by removing intersection loci of lower dimension; thus in each chart, each stratum is given by certain linear equations and linear inequalities in the local coordinates. For present purposes the detailed structure of these equations and inequalities is not needed.

Now recall our discussion in Section 2 of the difference in viewpoints between the study of Goursat distributions and the study of curvilinear data. From the former perspective, one cannot distinguish, at level 222, between regular and vertical data. Thus in the associated literature there is no possibility of using the symbol V2subscript𝑉2V_{2}; indeed, often the code words in (6.2) are truncated by removing the first two symbols. To say this another way, the choice of vertical directions at level 111 is somewhat arbitrary, and consequently the divisor at infinity I2subscript𝐼2I_{2} is not well-defined. Thus the stratification of a monster space is, with this viewpoint, slightly coarser than what we are using in this paper.

Our earliest studies of the monster (Semple) tower [6, 7, 8] were focused on deriving formulas in enumerative geometry for algebraic curves in the projective plane; thus we were concerned with orbits of the monster spaces under the action of the projective linear group PGL​(2)PGL2{\rm PGL}(2). In this context, one wants an even finer stratification, in which, at level 222, there are three sorts of points:

  1. 1)

    a general point of ℙ2​(2)superscriptℙ22\mathbb{P}^{2}(2) represents the curvilinear data of a nondegenerate conic at a point;

  2. 2)

    there is still a divisor at infinity, whose points represent the data of certain singular curves;

  3. 3)

    there is a second divisor whose points represents the data of lines, and this is a distinguished locus invariant under the action of the group.

From this viewpoint, there are three possible symbols for the second entry of a code word. In our cited works, the symbols were 00, −-, and ∞\infty; to pass to the code word of the present paper, replace 00 or −- by R𝑅R, and replace ∞\infty by V2subscript𝑉2V_{2}. In this finer stratification, there are eight strata at level 333, each of which happens to be a PGL​(2)PGL2{\rm PGL}(2)-orbit, as enumerated in [7, Theorem 2], rather than the five strata listed in Example 6.1 above or the two strata of the differential-geometric theory.

We now return to our analysis of the family acquiring a node.

Lemma 6.2.

Every point of a twig belongs to the same stratum, except possibly its nodes.

Proof.

There is a chart in which the entire twig appears as a coordinate axis, except that one of its nodes is at infinity. ∎

Thus to each twig we can associate the code word of its stratum, called its twig word. Similarly, the code word of the stratum containing a node will be called its node word. The node word of N​(p1​p2​⋯​pk)𝑁subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘N(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k}) will be denoted W​(p1​p2​⋯​pk)𝑊subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘W(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k}).

Theorem 6.3.

Suppose that 0≤j≤k−10𝑗𝑘10\leq j\leq k-1. The twig word of T​(p1​p2​⋯​pj)𝑇subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑗T(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{j}) (((a twig at level k)k) consists of W​(p1​p2​⋯​pj)𝑊subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑗W(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{j}) (((a node word at level j)j) followed by a single R𝑅R and a string of k−1−j𝑘1𝑗k-1-j occurrences of Vj+2subscript𝑉𝑗2V_{j+2}.

Note that if j=k−1𝑗𝑘1j=k-1, then the final string is empty.

Proof.

The map from S​(k)𝑆𝑘S(k) to S​(j+1)𝑆𝑗1S(j+1) is an isomorphism from T​(p1​p2​⋯​pj)𝑇subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑗T(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{j}) to the vertical curve over the node N​(p1​p2​⋯​pj)∈S​(j)𝑁subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑗𝑆𝑗N(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{j})\in S(j). (If k=j+1𝑘𝑗1k=j+1, the map is the identity.) The curvilinear data at level j+1𝑗1j+1 is thus regular: it represents a tangent direction at N​(p1​p2​⋯​pj)𝑁subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑗N(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{j}). Beyond this level we have the successive prolongations of this vertical curve and, as we have already observed, they lie within the spaces Ij+2​[n]subscript𝐼𝑗2delimited-[]𝑛I_{j+2}[n]. ∎

Lemma 6.4.

Consider the twig words of the two twigs meeting at N​(p1​p2​⋯​pk)𝑁subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘N(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k}). In each position, either the symbols agree, or one of the symbols is R𝑅R and the other is some Visubscript𝑉𝑖V_{i}. The node word W​(p1​p2​⋯​pk)𝑊subscript𝑝1subscript𝑝2⋯subscript𝑝𝑘W(p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{k}) can be deduced from these twig words as follows: in each position, if the symbols of the twig words agree, then use the common symbol; if they disagree, then use Visubscript𝑉𝑖V_{i} rather than R𝑅R.

Proof.

The divisors at infinity and their prolongations are closed loci. If the non-nodal points of a twig are contained in such a divisor or its prolongation, then so are the nodes of this twig. Thus if a symbol Visubscript𝑉𝑖V_{i} occurs in a certain position of a twig word, then the words of its nodes must have the same symbol in this position. For the same reason, the words of the two twigs meeting at a node cannot have differing V𝑉V’s in the same position. If both words have R𝑅R in some position, this means that the coordinates of the non-nodal points of both twigs satisfy a certain set of strict linear inequalities. Since each twig is a coordinate axis, the origin also satisfies these same inequalities. ∎

Using Theorem 6.3 and Lemma 6.4, one can recursively compute any desired node word or twig word, invoking the following base cases: W​(∅)=∅𝑊W(\varnothing)=\varnothing and W​(11​⋯​1)=W​(22​⋯​2)=R​R​⋯​R𝑊11⋯1𝑊22⋯2𝑅𝑅⋯𝑅W(11\cdots 1)=W(22\cdots 2)=RR\cdots R.

7 Speculations about other singularities

What should one expect if one carries out a similar analysis for a different sort of singular curve C𝐶C on a surface? If one prolongs the curve by itself, without reference to any family, one obtains its strict prolongation; for x​y=t𝑥𝑦𝑡xy=t that is simply the pair of end twigs. If one creates a one-dimensional family in which C𝐶C is the central member and all other members are nonsingular (a smoothing family), one expects that the construction of this paper will yield three sorts of structures:

  1. 1)

    a configuration of curves, consisting of the strict prolongation together with prolongations of certain vertical curves;

  2. 2)

    a one-dimensional cycle obtained by assigning an appropriate multiplicity to each curve in the configuration;

  3. 3)

    a scheme whose fundamental class is this cycle.

The authors of [15] consider a locally irreducible curve, e.g., the Ansubscript𝐴𝑛A_{n} singularity defined by y2=xn+1superscript𝑦2superscript𝑥𝑛1y^{2}=x^{n+1}, and define a configuration of curves of the type just described. Their analysis shows that their configuration matches the configuration one obtains by the standard process of embedded resolution by point blowups, with the prolongations of vertical curves naturally matching up with the exceptional divisors of the standard process. (See [12, Chapter 1] for an account of embedded resolution of curve singularities.) We think that the same configuration will emerge via prolongation of any smoothing family.

Embedded resolution produces even more: it associates a multiplicity to each exceptional divisor, and thus defines a cycle (in fact a divisor, since the entire configuration lies on a surface). Here again we speculate that the prolongation of any smoothing family will yield the same multiplicities, i.e., that the same cycle will emerge, no matter which smoothing family is used.

As for scheme structure, one should note that the versal deformation space is typically of higher dimension; for example, the versal deformation of the Ansubscript𝐴𝑛A_{n} singularity consists of all curves

y2=xn+1+tn​xn+tn−1​xn−1+⋯+t1​x+t0.superscript𝑦2superscript𝑥𝑛1subscript𝑡𝑛superscript𝑥𝑛subscript𝑡𝑛1superscript𝑥𝑛1⋯subscript𝑡1𝑥subscript𝑡0\displaystyle y^{2}=x^{n+1}+t_{n}x^{n}+t_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+t_{1}x+t_{0}.

One can obtain many different one-dimensional smoothing families by taking various curves within the base of the versal deformation. Here we anticipate that one can obtain many different limiting scheme structures on the central fiber, which reflect, in some fashion, the various directions of approach on the base. We hope to pursue these speculations further.
